WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:02.475
Here's an uncomfortable question.

2
00:00:02.475 --> 00:00:04.928
Is one shape declared twice in your repo?

3
00:00:04.928 --> 00:00:08.279
Your git history remembers the day the copies disagreed.

4
00:00:09.679 --> 00:00:16.162
Open your git log and read the fix commits — the ones that say sync this with that, or forgot to update.

5
00:00:16.162 --> 00:00:16.972
That's drift.

6
00:00:16.972 --> 00:00:17.969
Already shipped.

7
00:00:19.369 --> 00:00:26.632
So point your coding agent at your repo — Claude Code, Cursor, Copilot, whatever you run — and paste one message.

8
00:00:26.632 --> 00:00:28.946
Nothing installs, nothing is edited.

9
00:00:30.346 --> 00:00:37.277
It reads your code, your migrations, and your commit log, and builds a drift ledger — every row cites a file and line, or a commit.

10
00:00:37.277 --> 00:00:37.753
No vibes.

11
00:00:39.153 --> 00:00:48.618
In a blinded test on a real production codebase, it found an enum constraint that drifted across a hundred and forty-six migrations — fixed only after production errors.

12
00:00:48.618 --> 00:00:52.874
A column the database widened weeks earlier that the code didn't know about.

13
00:00:52.874 --> 00:00:55.730
And one field that took twenty-eight edits to land.

14
00:00:57.130 --> 00:01:03.381
And every finding names the verify gate that turns it into a build failure, not an incident.

15
00:01:03.381 --> 00:01:05.827
Not it might drift — it already did.

16
00:01:07.227 --> 00:01:08.532
It's built to say no.

17
00:01:08.532 --> 00:01:13.689
Verdicts include not a fit, and every report ships a what-you-will-not-get section.

18
00:01:13.689 --> 00:01:15.801
If yes, you get a first-week plan.

19
00:01:17.201 --> 00:01:22.044
One U R L — metaobjects dot dev slash assess dot em-dee.

20
00:01:22.044 --> 00:01:24.552
Worst case, your repo's fine.

21
00:01:24.552 --> 00:01:28.703
Best case, you stop shipping the same bug twice.

